<subSubSection id="C97E5A9E6090B2AC53BC0637BAF52D31" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="588F41687D8E517BA240535FBCB61CE7" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" type="mainText">Biology. Rarely forming ripe seed in Norden.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9D45209F27401A7FAD1B6130954D2151" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" type="mainText">
Taxonomy. 
<taxonomicName id="161116298765AFC93C8DB40DF31D0EC2" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="berlandieri">Chenopodium berlandieri</taxonomicName>
is widespread and morphologically variable in North America; several races have been described. Most of the plants collected in Norden (and all over Europe) have been referred to 
<taxonomicName id="8B60A0414F62A1D320C1B7FB936FA296" authority="(Murr) A. Zobel" authorityName="(Murr) A. Zobel" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="berlandieri" subSpecies="zschackei">
subsp. zschackei 
<authority id="72270AA7B7B4A8A93C0D4DF5961E8B03" pageId="22" pageNumber="26">(Murr) A. Zobel</authority>
</taxonomicName>
, which is also the most widespread race in North America and the only one reported from Canada. However, the variation has not been sufficiently studied in North America, and the use of infraspecific names for European casual material is premature. The relationship between 
<taxonomicName id="E4D6625FFD1E36261466F78BD8D1B995" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.bestMatchDistance="32" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="berlandieri">C. berlandieri</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="924E7B2CA786C193CD322C70BE829030" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.bestMatchDistance="345" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hircinum">C. hircinum</taxonomicName>
(20) should be studied 
<bibRef id="19DC2184B1D09CC626DDAFCAC1876884" pageId="22" pageNumber="26">(Bassett &amp; Crompton 1982)</bibRef>
; both are tetraploids with 2n=36.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E5654CA4AD56A46C6ABCF4EAB2255176" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="6500CB65C99D81FB7F06DB6D4647F299" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" type="mainText">
Similar taxa. 
<taxonomicName id="1ECAF3385C0877108B02BE53C21E82F4" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="berlandieri">Chenopodium berlandieri</taxonomicName>
in fruit is easily recognized by the honeycomb-pitted seeds. - In the vegetative state sometimes taken for 
<taxonomicName id="E7EA50AA7F202D11950969D107331C5C" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.bestMatchDistance="918" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="album">C. album</taxonomicName>
(15) or 
<taxonomicName id="917BDEB8CA86A3CEF836DE060E8FEAFF" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.bestMatchDistance="1610" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="opulifolium">C. opulifolium</taxonomicName>
(21), but distinguished from both by the combination of yellowish stem, distinctly acuminate and relatively long leaf-blades with few teeth, and winged tepals. - Sometimes also similar to C. hircinum (20), but not stinking and with narrower, less distinctly 3-lobed leaf-blades.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
